\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 9. P. scorzonerifolium} Vill.,{\i  Hist. Pl. Dauph.}{\b  2}: 519 (1787). Stem 30-90 cm. Basal leaves usually absent at anthesis, narrowly lanceolate to elliptical, usually narrowed gradually to the petiole; lower cauline leaves up to 15 × 1·5 cm, narrowly lanceolate to linear, few. Inflorescence usually cylindrical and lax, acute. Corolla pale bluish-lilac, rarely white.{\i  Meadows and wood margins. • S.W. & S.C. Alps, N. & C. Appennini.} Ga He It.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 10. P. zahlbruckneri} Vest,{\i  Steyerm. Zeitschr.}{\b  3}: 159 (1821) ({\i P. betonicifolium} subsp.{\i  zahlbruckneri }(Vest) Hayek). Stem 25-90 cm. Basal leaves mostly present at anthesis, lanceolate to ovate-lanceolate, rounded to shallowly cordate at base, long-petiolate; cauline leaves similar, but cuneate at base. Inflorescence cylindrical, rarely ovoid, eventually elongating and lax. Corolla deep blue. 2n = 24.{\i  Meadows and wood margins; calcifuge. • E. Alps and N.W. Jugoslavia.} Au Ju.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 11. P. betonicifolium} Vill.,{\i  Hist. Pl. Dauph.}{\b  2}: 518 (1787) (incl. {\i P. scaposum} R. Schulz). Stem 20-70 cm, erect, usually nearly leafless in the upper third. Basal leaves ovate-lanceolate to lanceolate, usually cordate, 1- to 2-crenate or crenate-serrate, long-petiolate, sometimes rosulate; cauline leaves similar but narrower. Spike cylindrical. Bracts setaceous, rarely lanceolate, inconspicuous. Corolla deep blue, nearly straight in bud. Stigmas 3, sometimes 4, rarely single flowers with 2. Seeds 0·4 × 0·2 mm. 2n = 24.{\i  Meadows and woods. • Alps and mountains of N. Italy.} Au Ga Ge He It.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 12. P. cordatum} Balbis, {\i Mém. Acad. Sci.} ({\i Turin}) {\b 16}: 208 (1809) ({\i P. balbisii} A. DC.). Stem 15-25 cm, flexuous. Basal leaves orbicular to reniform, long-petiolate; cauline leaves 4-7, rhombic to cordate-ovate, sharply and remotely serrate. Inflorescence more or less globose to oblong. Bracts very small. Corolla bluish-white. Stigmas 3. 2n = 24.{\i  Calcareous rocks. • Maritime Alps.} Ga It.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 13. P. orbiculare} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl.} 170 (1753). Stem (5-)10-50 cm, erect, rarely ascending, sparsely leafy. Basal leaves linear-lanceolate to elliptical, rounded to cordate, or narrowed into the petiole, crenate-serrate, petiolate; lower cauline leaves similar, the upper subsessile, serrate to entire. Inflorescence 1-2·5 cm across, more or less globose, with 15-30 flowers. Bracts more or less acuminate, ovate-lanceolate, entire or serrate, shorter to longer than the capitulum. Corolla blue to blue-violet, rarely white, strongly curved in bud. stigmas 2-3. 2n = 22+0-2B.{\i  Dry grassland and rocky ground; somewhat calcicole. • From S. England and Latvia southwards to S. Spain and Albania.} Al Au Be Br Cz Ga Ge He Hs Hu It Ju Po Rm Rs (B, C, W).
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28   Very variable in size, shape and development of leaves and shape, indumentum and length of bracts. Numerous variants have been described by R. Schulz, but these are connected by many intermediates and lack a clear geographical basis.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28   Among the more distinct variants are{\b  P. hispanicum} R. Schulz, {\i Monogr. Phyteuma }127 (1904), from S. Spain, with broadly elliptical to suborbicular basal leaves and bracts with regular, straight cilia, and {\b P. tenerum} R. Schulz,{\i  op. cit.} 122 (1904), from W.C. and S.W. Europe, with densely leafy stems, finely and sharply serrate leaves and small, triangular bracts. The taxonomic value of these variants requires further investigation.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 14. P. pseudorbiculare} Pant., {\i Verh. Ver. Nat. Heilk. Presburg} nov. ser.,{\b  2}: 53 (1874). Like {\b 13} but basal leaves more or less suborbicular, shortly petiolate; cauline broadly elliptical to suborbicular, diminishing in size less rapidly upwards, the upper more or less petiolate; bracts broadly ovate, often cordate at base, not abruptly acuminate, serrate.{\i  Pastures and rocks. • W. part of Balkan peninsula.} Al Ju.
\par 

